Over the weekend we lost two giants of the civil rights movement, Congressman John Lewis and C.T. Vivian. Both worked alongside Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. to lead the Civil Rights Movement. Both were beaten, arrested, and jailed fighting for the rights of Black people and for a more just nation. Rest in power.

"Do not get lost in a sea of despair. Be hopeful, be optimistic. Our struggle is not the struggle of a day, a week, a month, or a year, it is the struggle of a lifetime. Never, ever be afraid to make some noise and get in good trouble, necessary trouble." (Congressman John Lewis)

post_text:
Springfield Prep will be closed tomorrow, Wednesday, 6/3 for a Day of Solidarity and remote learning will not take place. As individuals and as an organization, we have been processing and grieving the killing of George Floyd and the racism, discrimination, and violence our Black colleagues, families, and students face every day.

Many in our community are upset and exhausted. We are taking this day to provide space to our community members to process, grieve, act, learn, or care for themself and their loved ones.

Whatever you choose to do, please know that the Springfield Prep community stands with you.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Another #TeacherAppreciation post!

Even after the school day is over, there is always more learning to be done! This month, members of our teaching and culture teams have worked together to produce a weekly webinar series in honor of #AAPIHeritageMonth. The series goes live every Wednesday at 4 p.m. and gives staff and students the opportunity to learn about and discuss Asian and Pacific Island cultures together.

Today, we explored the countries of Central and North Asia and learned some new words in Russian! #EdThatAddsUp

With little notice, these amazing educators brought their classrooms online, and have continued to support our scholars and their families without missing a beat. They're hosting 1:1 and small group Zoom meetings with students, having weekly phone conversations with parents, collaborating with their colleagues, and to top it all off they're sharing extra videos, photos, read alouds and scholar shout-outs to keep their students motivated and focused. THANK YOU!

This week is #TeacherAppreciationWeek, but we know that isn't nearly enough time to recognize and celebrate the amazing work our teachers do day in and day out! With little notice, these amazing educators brought their classrooms online, and have continued to support our scholars and their families without missing a beat. They're hosting 1:1 and small group Zoom meetings with students, having weekly phone conversations with parents, collaborating with their colleagues, and to top it all off they're sharing extra videos, photos, read alouds and scholar shout-outs to keep their students motivated and focused. THANK YOU!

post_text:
As we come to the end of our first two weeks of closure, we are blown away by the resiliency of our #SpringfieldPrepFamily. Our team has worked tirelessly to distribute more than 1300 meals to families, provide 650 remote learning packets, and develop new and creative ways to connect with students and families. Our teachers are hosting daily virtual read alouds, classroom Zoom hangouts, and sharing daily resources, art prompts and fitness challenges for our scholars- and our student response has been amazing!

Check out Ms. Yiannos's recent read aloud of "The Giving Tree", and stay tuned for more updates and resources!

https://youtu.be/eDz1qR59RBk

This #HispanicHeritageMonth our scholars are exploring cultures through food, books, and art! Today our kindergarten students showed off their Carnival masks, our 3rd graders taught us all about places like Guatemala and Puerto Rico (did you know Puerto Rico has the only tropical rainforest in North America!?), and our 5th graders shared what they've learned about notable figures like Sylvia Mendez, Dolores Huerta, and Cesar Chavez.

Today our scholars took some time outside of the classroom to learn new skills and hear about some exciting future careers!

First, Mr. Justin joined our elementary students to share all about how his love for languages and social studies lead him to his career as an Anthropologist. When he asked "Who else loves Social Studies!?" there were lots of straight, silent hands!

Then, our 5th graders ended the day checking out our new enrichment programs- cooking, photography, graffiti art, improv comedy, student government, coding, and school newspaper. They jumped right in making salsa, discussing the emotions different kinds of photos can create, and designing their campaign posters for our first-ever student election! Belle's platform? "More Fun Fridays"!

You got it, Belle!

#EdThatAddsUp #DreamBig

At Springfield Prep, we put FIRST things, first! To showcase our core values (Focus, Integrity, Respect, Self-Determination, and Teamwork) we celebrated with a whole school presentation at the end of the year.

Our scholars showed focus while being living wax museum characters, created new cheers for Integrity, showed teamwork by singing "You Got A Friend In Me" (in English and in Spanish!), performed a remix of the Aretha Franklin classic "Respect", and shared some reflections about a time where someone they know showed Self Determination. #TBT #EdThatAddsUp #SpringfieldPrepFamily

Our scholars have been working hard all month long reading, researching, and learning about notable African Americans in honor of Black History Month. Today, they got to share their work with family and friends at our Black History Month Celebration!

Our kindergartners kicked things off with a recitation of the "I Have A Dream Speech" by Dr. King. Our first graders shared powerful quotes from the book "Martin's Big Words". We learned all about Garrett Augustus Morgan (the inventor of the street light), Frederick Douglass and Harriet Tubman. The Celebration ended with a special performance of "Lift Ev'ry Voice and Sing" by our very own Mrs.Mitchell! #SpringfieldPrepFamily #BlackHistoryMonthCelebration #EdThatAddsUp

Did you know these facts about Sojourner Truth?

1. A former slave, Sojourner Truth became an outspoken advocate for abolition, temperance, and civil and womenâ€™s rights in the nineteenth century. Her work during the Civil War earned her an invitation to meet President Abraham Lincoln in 1864.

2. In 1844, she became a resident of Florence, MA and a member of an abolitionist organization called the Northampton Association of Education and Industry, where she effectively launched her career as an equal rights activist.

3. During the Civil War, she was befriended by Susan B. Anthony and Elizabeth Cady Stanton to take up the issue of women's suffrage.

#FunFactFriday #BlackHistoryMonth #EdThatAddsUp

link:
Did you know these facts about The Obama Family?

1. Barack Obama won the Nobel Peace Prize in October 2009 for his extraordinary efforts at international diplomacy and foreign policy, especially with the Muslim world.

2. Former First Lady Michelle Obama attended Princeton University and Harvard Law School. After she graduated she began working at a Chicago law firm, where she met her husband, Barack.

3. Malia Obama was taught how to drive, steer and park by the secret service! Due to Barack Obama's high-profile security needs, the President wasn't allowed to be in a car alone with his daughter.

4. Sasha Obama landed herself a summer job at Nancy's, a seafood restaurant on the island of Martha's Vineyard! Also, Sasha's real name is actually "Natasha".

#FunFactFriday #BlackHistoryMonth #EdThatAddsUp

link:
Did you know these facts about Harriet Tubman?

1. Her Underground Railroad nickname was Moses because she sang spiritual songs for directions along the Railroad to freedom. She used the stars and mosses in the woods to guide her escapees.

2. The estimated number of slaves she helped range as high as 3,000. She never lost a single passenger.

3. She was an active proponent of women's suffrage and worked alongside women such as Susan B. Anthony. She also worked for the Union Army as a cook, a nurse and even a spy.

#FunFactFriday #BlackHistoryMonth #EdThatAddsUp
